[Other diseases to be taken into consideration in relation to
international trade in ruminants are bluetongue and other
(_Culicoides_-borne) orbiviruses. _Culicoides_ vectors are known to be
prevalent in the Middle East; Middle Eastern countries are major
importers of live ruminants. Some BTV serotypes in the Americas,
Africa, Australia, Europe, and distant parts of Asia are exotic to the
Middle East. The serotypes known to have been identified in Colombia
are BTV 12, 14, and 17 (Refs 1 and 2). Other orbiviruses, namely
epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD_ serotypes 1 and 2, were reported
there as well (Ref 1).

The risk of pathogen movement to receptive ecosystems (where efficient
vectors may be present and active at the time of arrival), depends
upon several factors, including the seasons prevailing in the source
and target regions within the exporting and importing countries during
the export period, and the duration of the transportation. The risk
can be minimized by various measures, including tests, as well as by
taking into consideration the said factors. - Mod.AS]

References
----------
1. EJ Homan, WP Taylor, HL de Ruiz, TM Yuill: Bluetongue virus and
epizootic haemorrhagic disease of deer virus serotypes in northern
Colombian cattle. J Hyg (Lond). 1985 Aug; 95(1): 165-72; available at
<http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2129503/>.

2. IA Lager (2004). Bluetongue virus in South America: overview of
viruses, vectors, surveillance and unique features. Vet Ital 2004;
40(3): 89-93; available at
<http://www.izs.it/vet_italiana/2004/03/19.pdf>.

